{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480463"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:44:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:44:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"56"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"56","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/56"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.05,0.16,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"56"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107039"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"56","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/56"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"56"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89504"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"133"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107039"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department with abdominal distension and progressive lethargy, associated with altered sleep wake cycle and confusion. This follows a similar episode a month prior, with self-discharge from hospital preventing ongoing management since this time. Relevant past medical history includes liver cirrhosis related to hepatitis C and ongoing alcohol misuse. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears jaundiced and cachectic. He is oriented to place, but not to time or person. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has normal eye movements. A hepatic flap is present and there are petechiae on his chest. His abdomen is distended with shifting dullness but no tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to IV thiamine, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rifaximin","Diuretics","TIPSS","Therapeutic paracentesis","Lactulose"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent episodes of hepatic encephalopathy and ascites, which are worrying complications of decompensated cirrhosis and indicate a poor prognosis. \u003Cstrong\u003ELactulose \u003C/strong\u003Eis the treatment of choice for hepatic encephalopathy. It works by reducing the absorption of ammonia in the gut. In addition to lactulose, \u003Cstrong\u003ERifaximin \u003C/strong\u003Eis an effective treatment for management of hepatic encephalopathy, though this is typically reserved for cases which are refractory to management with lactulose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiuretics \u003C/strong\u003Eare frequently used in the management of patient with ascites, in conjunction with a low salt diet. This is effective in controlling ascites in approximately 95% of cases. However, in the immediate setting, these should be used with caution due to the risks of acute kidney injury. Until the patient\u0027s renal function is known, these should not be used. Any evidence of acute kidney injury should first be management with intravenous albumin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E involves draining ascitic fluid through a needle inserted into the abdomen. While it can provide immediate relief of ascites, it does not prevent recurrence and is not a first-line management. It should be reserved for patients who do not tolerate diuretics or have ongoing ascites despite diuretic use. Furthermore, like diuretics it carries the risk of hypotension and acute kidney injury, which must be addressed prior to paracentesis with intravenous albumin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ETIPSS procedure\u003C/strong\u003E (transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt) can effectively control ascites by reducing portal hypertension. However, it can worsen hepatic encephalopathy by allowing more toxins to bypass the liver, and is mainly indicated in cases of refractory ascites requiring frequent therapeutic paracentesis. It is not an appropriate choice in this patient with encephalopathy who has not adequately trialled medical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of thiamine with lactulose for this patient with decompensated alcohol and hepatitis C related cirrhosis and hepatic encephalopathy. Additional therapy may well include albumin replacement, diuretics, rifaximin, diagnostic ascitic fluid aspirate, antibiotics and nutritional support. When the patient\u0027s condition improves, it is crucial to provide counselling, education, and psychosocial support to help him understand his condition and the need for ongoing care. This approach can improve treatment adherence and prevent future episodes of decompensation. The overall prognosis remains poor without significant lifestyle changes and adherence to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lactulose is the first-line treatment in the management of encephalopathy in patients with cirrhosis.","Rifaximin is effective for the management of hepatic encephalopathy but is typically reserved for patients refractory to lactulose.","Diuretics and therapeutic paracentesis are useful in the management of ascites. However caution must be taken in patients presenting with decompensated cirrhosis, due to the risk of acute kidney injury.","Patient education and psychosocial support are crucial for improving adherence to treatment in chronic liver disease."],"references":["Acharya C, Bajaj JS. Current Management of hepatic encephalopathy. Am J Gastroenterol. 2018; 113:1600-12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30002466/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"56"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T20:48:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T21:14:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"56"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107039"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",